# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The problem can be solved using a linear dynamic programming approach. We maintain a linear sequence (the given string "word") and use the values of previous states to compute the current state.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- For `dp[0]`, we set it to 2 since for one character, 2 additions are needed to form "abc". This is our base case.
- For each subsequent character, if the current character is greater than the previous character, we can decrease the number of additions required by 1. Otherwise, we increase the number of additions required by 2.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$, where n is the length of the input string.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$, where n is the length of the input string.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int addMinimum(string word) {
        int n = word.size();
        vector<int> dp(n);
        dp[0] = 2;
        for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i)
            dp[i] = word[i] > word[i-1] ? dp[i-1] - 1 : dp[i-1] + 2;
        return dp[n-1];
    }
};
```

