# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The idea here is every character should be valid.
'a' will be valid if 'b' follows it similarly,
'b' will be valid if 'c' follows it and 
'c' will be valid if it is last or 'a' follows it.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Now when the character is not valid:
- when 'a' is followed by 'a'
so in this case we will be adding "bc" after 'a' i.e performing 2 operations (we are not actully adding in string).
- when 'a' is followed by 'c'
so in this case we will be adding "b" after 'a' i.e performing 1 operation (we are not actully adding in string).
- when 'a is followed by 'b' its already a valid case, so no need to perform any operation. REPEAT SIMILAR STEPS FOR 'b' and 'c'

- THE MAIN IDEA HERE IS WE DO NOT WORRY ABOUT PREV CHARCATERS AS THEY ARE ALREADY TAKEN CARE OF.
- MEANS PREV CHAR HAS DONE ITS OPERATION AND HAS MADE STRING VALID TILL CURRENT CHAR. 
- NOTE:we've to make first letter 'a' in order to begin with algorithm and we have to take care of last char seprately
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
