# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Keep string "abc" and match somehow 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Keep given string w="abc"
and at index i, string matching it with w
suppose matching at 
"abc"

"a b b c c a a c"
 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7
a matches with a, we increment both counters, b matches with b, again increment, but b and c does not match, so we **determine the count**=2 matched characters.

Next **directly move to 2nd index** as 1st index is already included in previous match 

Now, we are not only incrementing counters when character of w matches with word, but when character of word is **greater than w's character also**,

**word[j]>=w[k]**

Consider next iteration
we get after matching "bc"
we only have to add "a" to it.

another example at 6th index, we will get "ac" after matching as
a matched with a 
b matched with c as **c>=b**

Here we only have to insert "a" in between.

 **Also consider,** 
the condition word[j]>=w[k] might repeat characters, as 

abc will get matched with "bb" as
a with b as b>=a
b with b as b>=b

abc will get matched with "cb" as
a with c as c>=a
b with b as b>=b

which is **wrong**
So make sure while matching,
1. **same character does not gets repeated** 
2. **they do not get matched in decreasing order**

therefore I added the condition :  if(j>i && word[j-1]>=word[j]) break;

Once determined the count at an iteration, subtract it with length of "abc" and add it to final Answer


# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(N)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

