Brute Force is pretty staright forward, Optimal solution can be solved using variation of sliding Window

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
This is the implementation of the function `distinctDifferenceArray`, which takes a vector of integers `v` as input and returns another vector `ans`. The purpose of this function is to calculate the distinct difference array of the input vector.

The distinct difference array of a vector `v` is another vector `ans` such that `ans[i]` is the number of distinct values in the subvector `v[0:i]` of `v` after taking the differences of adjacent elements.

The function first initializes two maps `m1` and `m2` to keep track of the frequency of each element in the subvector `v[0:i]` and `v[i+1:n-1]` respectively. It then loops through the input vector `v` and updates the maps `m1` and `m2` accordingly.

For each element `v[i]`, the function increments the frequency of `v[i]` in `m1` and removes it from `m2` if its frequency becomes zero. It then calculates the difference in size between `m1` and `m2`, which represents the number of distinct values in the subvector `v[0:i]` after taking the differences of adjacent elements. This value is appended to the `ans` vector.

Finally, the function returns the `ans` vector.

