# Intuition
The code aims to calculate the difference in the count of distinct elements between the left and right subarrays for each position in the input array `nums`. This difference is then stored in the `answer` vector.

# Approach
The approach involves iterating through the input array `nums` and, for each position `i`, calculating the count of distinct elements in the left subarray (from index 0 to i) and the count of distinct elements in the right subarray (from index i+1 to the end). The difference in these counts is then appended to the `answer` vector.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n^2)$$, where n is the length of the input array `nums`. This is because, for each element in `nums`, we calculate the difference in distinct elements between the left and right subarrays, which involves traversing these subarrays.

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$, where n is the length of the input array `nums`. We use two unordered sets, `left` and `right`, to store distinct elements in the left and right subarrays, respectively.

# Code Explanation
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> distinctDifferenceArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<int> answer;  // Initialize a vector to store the differences in distinct elements

        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            // Create an unordered set for distinct elements in the left subarray (from 0 to i)
            unordered_set<int> left(nums.begin(), nums.begin() + i + 1);

            // Create an unordered set for distinct elements in the right subarray (from i+1 to end)
            unordered_set<int> right(nums.begin() + i + 1, nums.end());

            // Calculate the difference in the counts of distinct elements between left and right subarrays
            answer.push_back(left.size() - right.size());
        }

        return answer;  // Return the vector containing differences in distinct elements
    }
};
```

