# Intuition
Since we want to have a difference of left and right entities of an ith element, it is advisable to maintain two separate arrays one to the left of ith (here ith element is included in left side) and other to the right of ith element to make things simpler and easy to operate on.

# Approach
Since we want count of unique elements it is intuitive to use a hashset, so use a hashset first from left end and keep storing the result in your leftDis array, similarly do it from right end.
And finally take the differences in a separate array( you can use either of leftDis or rightDis array also to store final result, you can skip using third array).

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
Since every element is visited twice at max.
TC is 2*n which is O(N).

- Space complexity:
We have used 2 or 3 arrays of N size.
So space complexity also becomes O(N).

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int[] distinctDifferenceArray(int[] nums) {
       HashSet<Integer> hs = new HashSet<>();
       int[] leftDis = new int[nums.length];
       int[] rightDis = new int[nums.length];

       for(int i=0; i<nums.length; i++){
           hs.add(nums[i]);
           leftDis[i]=hs.size();
        }

        //refresh the same array as a new one for rightside.
        hs = new HashSet<Integer>();

        hs.add(nums[nums.length-1]);

        for(int i=nums.length-2; i>=0; i--){
            rightDis[i]=hs.size();
            hs.add(nums[i]);            
        }

        int[] ans = new int[nums.length];

        for(int i=0; i<nums.length; i++){
            ans[i]=leftDis[i]-rightDis[i];
        }

        return ans; 
    }
}
```

