# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We start by checking the binary representation of the numbers.

Let's take an example: 

`nums = [1,2], k = 2`

We write the numbers in their binary represenations.

1 -> `1` | 2 -> `10`

**Observation 1:** The maximum number that can be made is by multiplying the number with maximum number of bits in it's binary representation.

In this example, we have k = 2, We have 3 cases:
- We use both operations for `idx: 0` then we will convert 1 (`1`) -> 4 (`100`) and our result will be `4 | 2 = 6`
- We use one operation for `idx: 0` and the second one for `idx: 1` then we will convert 1 (`1`) -> 2 (`10`) and 2 (`10`) -> 4 (`100`) and our result will be `2 | 4 = 6`
- We use both for `idx: 1` then we will convert 2 (`10`) -> 8 (`1000`) and our result will be `1 | 8 = 9`

It can be observed that performing the operations on the number which has highest number of bits can give us the maximum result, which is `9` for this example.

Here's the second case what if we have multiple numbers sharing the maximum number of bits.

Let's take an example again:

`nums = [12,9], k = 2`

Here we have 12 -> `1100` and 9 -> `1001`

Both of them have maximum number of bits which is 4. Here we have k = 2.

 - Supose we apply first operation on `idx: 0` then it will become 12 (`1100`) -> 24 (`11000`) and the other number would be 9 (`1001`)
 - Now we only applied one operation and we still have one operation left (initially `k=2`)
 - Now our array is `[24, 9]`
 - Now we can see that 24 (`11000`) has maximum number of bits and according to the `Observation 1`, applying all operations on it will give us the maximum result for the array -> `[24, 9]`
 - After apply the rest of the operations on `24` our array becomes `[48, 9]` our final result becomes `48 | 9 = 57`

Now we apply the same thing we `idx: 1`
- Apply one operation then it will become 9 (`1001`) -> 18 (`10010`).
- Our new array is `[12, 18]`
- Now we can see that 18 (`10010`) has maximum number of bits and according to the `Observation 1`, applying all operations on it will give us the maximum result for the array -> `[12, 18]`
- After apply the rest of the operations on `18` our array becomes `[12, 36]` our final result becomes `12 | 36 = 44`

Now our final answer for the array `[12, 9]` and `k=2` will be the maximum of `57` and `44` which is `57`.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Base Case: If the size of the input is `1` we can just return `nums[0]*k`
- Now we loop over the input array and for each index we use all the operations on the current index that is `nums[idx]*k`
To calculate the answer for this index, we also need the OR of the rest of the elements. For this we use prefix and suffix array.
- We build the prefix and suffix array.
```
        vector<long long> pref(n+1), suff(n+1);


        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            pref[i + 1] = pref[i] | nums[i];
        }

        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            suff[i] = suff[i + 1] | nums[i];
        }
```
- To calucalte the answer for the current index we have three thing to consider `pref[i]`, `nums[idx]*k` and `suff[i+1]`.
- The result for current index will be `pref[i] | nums[idx] * k | suff[i+1]`
- Our final answer will be the maximum of the results we get from each index.


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
- Here we are computing prefix OR on the fly.
```
class Solution {
public:
    typedef long long ll;

    long long maximumOr(vector<int> &nums, int k) {
        int n = nums.size();
        if(n == 1)
            return nums[0]*1LL << k;

        vector<ll> suff(n+1);

        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            suff[i] = suff[i + 1] | nums[i];
        }

        int preOR = 0;

        ll ans = 0;
        for(int i =0; i < n; i++) {
            ll curr = nums[i]*1LL << k;
            ll tmp = preOR | curr | suff[i+1];
            preOR |= nums[i];
            ans = max(ans, tmp);
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

