# Intuition
Let `n = nums.length`
Let's assume $k = 1$. We can multiply each number by $2$ one-by-one and for each we will calculate `nums[0] | nums[1] | ... | nums[n - 1]`. The answer will be maximum among all of this.
Now let's say $k \gt 1$. For each $k$ we have $n$ choices to pick. But rathar then picking other element, it is always better to pick an element which was giving maximum answer for $k = 1$ and multiply it further for $k - 1$ times and take maximum for answer.
So, in general we can multiply each number by $2^k$ one-by-one and for each we will calculate `nums[0] | nums[1] | ... | nums[n - 1]`. The answer will be maximum among all of this.

# Approach
- Store the total bitcount for each index from $0$ to $63$ in `bits` array. (this array will be used to calculate `nums[0] | nums[1] | ... | nums[n - 1]` in nearly $O(1)$ time)
- For each `t` in `nums`
    - Remove the actual bitcount of `t` from `bits` array
    - Multiply it by $2$
    - Add the new bitcount in `bits` array. if bitcount at this index is > 0 then add it the `curr` answer
    - Remove the new bitcount and add the actual one to get back to original state
- Take maximum of `curr` for each `t` 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $O(n)$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $O(1)$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```java
class Solution {
    public long maximumOr(int[] nums, int k) {
        long bits[] = new long[64];
        for(int i = 0;i < nums.length;i++){
            for(int j = 0;j < 64;j++){
                bits[j] += (((long)nums[i] >> j) & 1);
            }
        }
        long max = 0;
        for(int i = 0;i < nums.length;i++){
            long t = nums[i];
            for(int j = 0;j < 64;j++){
                bits[j] -= ((t >> j) & 1); // removing actual bitcount
            }
            t *= (1L << k);
            long curr = 0;
            for(int j = 0;j < 64;j++){
                bits[j] += ((t >> j) & 1); // adding new bitcount
                if(bits[j] > 0) curr |= (1L << j);
                bits[j] -= ((t >> j) & 1); // removing new bitcount
                bits[j] += (((long)nums[i] >> j) & 1); // adding actual bitcount
            }
            max = Math.max(max,curr);
        }
        return max;
    }
}
```

