# Intuition
- A previous xor preXor[i] contains all previous numbers' xor;
- A subsequent xor subXor[i] contains all subsequent numbers xor;
- preXor[i] | subXor[i] = xor of all numbers except nums[i];
- If shifting nums[i]'s bits 1 time makes the max xor, then nums[i] must has the highest '1' bit, therefore, all k shifts should be performed on nums[i].

# Approach
Calculate preXor;
Calculate subXor;
For nums[i], shift nums[i], and xor with preXor[i] and subXor[i], keep the biggest result as the answer.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)

- Space complexity: O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long maximumOr(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        vector<int> preXor(nums.size(), 0); // All previous numbers xor.
        vector<int> subXor(nums.size(), 0); // All subsequent numbers xor.

        for(int i = 1; i < preXor.size(); ++i){
            preXor[i] = preXor[i - 1] | nums[i - 1];
        }

        for(int i = subXor.size() - 2; i >= 0; --i){
            subXor[i] = subXor[i + 1] | nums[i + 1];
        }

        long long answer = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); ++i){
            // 1. preXor[i] | subXor[i] = xor of all numbers except nums[i]
            // 2. if shifting nums[i]'s bits 1 time makes the max xor, then nums[i] must has the highest '1' bit, therefore, all k shifts should be on nums[i].
            answer = max(answer, (nums[i] * 1ll << k) | preXor[i] | subXor[i]); 
        }

        return answer;
    }
};
```

