solutions.content:
This is a fascinating one; we might be tempted to just multiply the larger number, but the first example already shows that it is not the most efficient strategy, since we might get all but one bits that are already covered by other numbers or anyway less than what we would get from multiply other numbers.

For example, for `12` (`1100` in binary) and `9` (`1001` in binary), we woul have the two scenarios with `k == 1`:

```cpp
11000 // 24, multiplying 12
01001
-----
11001 // 25, after ORing


01100
10010 // 18, multiplying 9
-----
11110 // 30, after ORing
```

So, while we now know there is not super-quick way to figure out which number is more suited to the multiplication, we can prove that we can go greedy and only always multiply the same number; for example, in the following example, with `k == 4`, the two alternatives worth considering would be:

```cpp
11000000 // 192, multiplying 12 by 2 4 times
00001001
-----
11001001 // 201, after ORing


00001100
10010000 // 144, multiplying 9 by 2 4 times
-----
10011100 // 156, after ORing
```

There is no way that we might get any larger number other than concentrating all our multiplications in only one, since we would get smaller most significant (ie: leftmost) bits that way (for example, multiplying each one by `2` twice, we would get `110000` and `100100`, which are clearly inferior).

Now, what we need to do, is to try each possible number; but can we do so efficiently?

The answer is yes; and we can do in constant space too - unlike most other solutions I spotted here (at least reading the titles), I did not bother building prefix and suffix arrays, but just computed the overall ORed value of reducing `nums` with that bitwise operator (which I called `tot`), for starters.

From there, we can derive the value we would have had without ORing a specific number `n` by removing the `1` bits that are unique to `n`.

For example, if we had:

```cpp
011101100001
100110100010
110110000001
010010001001
------------
111111001011 // ORed total
```

We can now compute what would have been the total ORed value without the first number `11101100001` seeing that it is the only one having the seventh and tenth least significant (ie: rightmost) bits flagged to `1`. In other words `001001000000` is a set of bits unique to the first digit and we remove it from the ORed total, we can get what would have been the value of ORing all the other numbers and we can easily do so with a XOR:

```cpp
001001000000 // bits unique to the first number
  |  |       // the ones that are just 0s in all the other columns
011101100001
100110100010
110110000001
010010001001
------------
111111001011 // ORed total

111111001011 // XORing
001001000000
------------
110110001011 // value we would get ORing all numbers but the first
```

Rinse and repeat for each number and we can compute what values multiplied by `2` `k` times and ORed with the rest would give us the largest value.

Now, to code all of this, let's start with our usual support variables:
* `tot` will store our overall ORed total;
* `tmp` and `copyN` will store copy of `tot` and the number we are parsing respectively, in the second loop;
* `res` is our usual result variable, preset to `0` (the lowest value we can get if `nums` does not have a single bit flagged on);
* `bits` will be our frequency map for each bit, just to know which bits are unique to each number; granted, given the range we would only need `30` cells, but I liked the round digit;
* `pos` will help us to know which bit we are writing in when mapping their frequence.

In our first loop, for each value `n` in `nums`, we will:
* update `tot` ORing `n` into it;
* reset `pos` to `0`;
* parse each bit of `n`, looping `while` `n != 0` and:
    * if the current least significant bit is active (ie: `n & 1`), we will increase the frequency of the bit at the current position (ie: `bits[pos]`) by `1`;
    * preparing for the next iteration, we will advance `pos` by `1`;
    * we will shave the least significant digit from `n`, right shifting the number by `1` position (ie: `n >>= 1`).

In our second loop, again for each `n` in `nums`, we will:
* copy `tot` into `tmp`;
* copy `n` into `copyN`;
* reset `pos` to `0`;
* parse each bit of `n`, looping `while` `n != 0` and:
    * if the current least significant bit is active (ie: `n & 1`) and it was the only time we encountered it (ie: `bits[pos] == 1`), we will flip it to `0` in `tmp` with a XOR operation (ie: `tmp ^= (1 << pos)`);
    * preparing for the next iteration, we will advance `pos` by `1`;
    * we will shave the least significant digit from `n`, right shifting the number by `1` position (ie: `n >>= 1`).
* update `res` to be the maximum between its current value and the result of all the numbers but `copyN` ORed (ie: `tmp`) ORed by `copyN` multiplied by `2` `k` times (ie: `copyN << k`).

Finally, we can `return` `res` :)

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$

# Code
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    long long maximumOr(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        // support variables
        long long tot = 0, tmp, copyN, res = 0;
        int bits[32] = {0}, pos;
        // computing tot and populating bits
        for (int n: nums) {
            tot |= n;
            pos = 0;
            while (n) {
                if (n & 1) bits[pos]++;
                pos++;
                n >>= 1;
            }
        }
        // trying each number
        for (int n: nums) {
            tmp = tot, copyN = n;
            pos = 0;
            while (n) {
                if ((n & 1) && bits[pos] == 1) tmp ^= (1 << pos);
                pos++;
                n >>= 1;
            }
            res = max(res, tmp | (copyN << k));
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Can we do better? Bien s\xFBr!

We can proceed as before with the first loop, then, right at the end of it, we can iterate `bits` and create a bitmask of `uniqueBits`.

Then we have two case:
* if there are no unique bits (ie: `uniqueBits == 0`), we will just try to OR the value of every number `n` shifted `k` times to `tot` and `return` the largest one we can get;
* if we have them, we can loop like in the previous loop, but at a much faster pace, creating a `bitmask` of unique bits presents in each number `n` (ie: `n & uniqueBits`) and then XOR it away from `tot`, computing `res` as before, just faster.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$

# Code

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    long long maximumOr(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        // support variables
        long long tot = 0, tmp, res = 0, uniqueBits = 0, bitmask;
        int bits[32] = {0}, pos;
        // computing tot and populating bits
        for (int n: nums) {
            tot |= n;
            pos = 0;
            while (n) {
                if (n & 1) bits[pos]++;
                pos++;
                n >>= 1;
            }
        }
        // populating uniqueBits
        for (int i = 0, currBit = 1; i < 31; i++, currBit <<= 1) {
            if (bits[i] == 1) uniqueBits |= currBit;
        }
        // edge case: no unique bits, so we just greedily get the biggest number we can
        if (!uniqueBits) {
            for (long long n: nums) res = max(res, tot | (n << k));
        }
        // trying each number
        for (long long n: nums) {
            bitmask = n & uniqueBits, tmp = tot ^ bitmask;
            res = max(res, tmp | (n << k));
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

