# Intuition
The most tricky point is to understnad that the biggiest result of `nums[0] | nums[1]...`  will be in case all `k` shift left will be done for one number, becase `1` bits will take the most left postions and `or` operation on such number will return the max value.

We just need to check all numbers to find witch one shift operation must be applied.
At this point task become quite similar to [238](https://leetcode.com/problems/product-of-array-except-self/)
We need to precalculate suffix sum (`or` operation in this task instead of tipical `+`) to avoid O(n^2) complexity. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)

- Space complexity: O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public long maximumOr(int[] nums, int k) {
        int[] right = new int[nums.length + 1];
        for (int i=nums.length - 1; i>=0; i--) {
            right[i] = right[i + 1] | nums[i];
        }

        long max = 0;
        int curr = 0;
        for (int i=0; i<nums.length; i++) {
            long local = (((long) nums[i]) << k) | curr | right[i + 1];

            max = Math.max(max, local);
            curr |= nums[i];
        }
        return max;
    }
}
```

