solutions.content:
# Intuition
To obtain the max value, we should do `k` opeations on **only one element**.

So the question becomes **which element** we should choose to operate on, in order to obtain the max value.

Think what if the question is not to obtain the max `OR` of all the element, but the max **sum** of all the element? We can sum up all the numbers, say `sum`; and then for each element `n`, calculate `sum - n + (n << k)`, choose the max one.

But what's the inverse operation of `OR`? In this case, we need only to *un-OR* **only one** element, so we can **keep track of which bits appear only once, and which bits appear more than twice**; for each *un-OR* operation, **clear the bits which only appear once**.

# Approach
After describing the *un-OR* operation, we can come up with the approach: calculate the `OR` of all the elements, say, `overall_or`; for each element `n`, calculate the value of (`overall_or` *un_OR* `n`) OR `n << k`, and return the maximum value. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $\mathcal{O}(n)$, since we iterate over `nums` twice, once for `OR`, once for calculate the reqired value.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $\mathcal{O}(1)$, since we only keep track of which bits appear more than once, and which appear more than twice.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
typedef long long ll;
typedef pair<ll, ll> pll;

class Solution {
public:
    long long maximumOr(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        // p.first is the overall_or
        // p.second is the bits which appear more than once
        pll p{0, 0};
        for (ll n: nums) {
            ll x = n & p.first; // those bits must appear more than onc
            p.first |= n; // overall_or
            p.second |= x; // bits appear more than once
        }
        ll result = 0;
        for (ll n: nums) {
            // (n & ~p.second) are bits that appear only once
            result = max(result, ((p.first & ~(n & ~p.second)) | (n << k)));
        }
        return result;
    }
};
```

