solutions.content:
Due to problem constraints, **the best strategy is to select a single number from the array and shift it by K.** To achieve this efficiently, we should precompute the array's results without any shifts. For each element, we subtract it from the precomputed result and apply a K-shift using the bitwise OR operation to update the result. However, one issue arises since the bitwise OR operation is a destructive operation, and we cannot reverse it for a single number. Therefore, we need to manually perform bit counting by utilizing the update method.

```
class Solution {
    void update(int[] bits, int n, int op) {
        for (int i = 0; i < bits.length; ++i) {
            if ((n & (1 L << i)) != 0) {
                bits[i] += op;
            }
        }
    }

    int toInt(int[] bits) {
        int r = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < bits.length; ++i) {
            if (bits[i] > 0) {
                r |= 1 << i;
            }
        }
        return r;
    }

    public long maximumOr(int[] nums, int k) {
        int[] bits = new int[32];
        for (int n: nums) {
            update(bits, n, 1);
        }
        long r = toInt(bits);
        for (int n: nums) {
            update(bits, n, -1);
            long m = toInt(bits);
            m |= (long) n << k;
            r = Math.max(r, m);
            update(bits, n, 1);
        }
        return r;
    }
}
```

