# Intuition
The intuition for this is very easy.
You just look at the right most and left most letters and see if they are same.
If yes, do nothing and check the next elements from left and right.
If no, check which letter is lexicographically small and replace the larger letter with smaller one.

In Java, Strings are immutable, that is, we cannot change the letters of a string at particular index.
Hence we are using StringBuilder here which has a built in method called setCharAt(index,char)

# Approach
1. This is a Two Pointer problem
2. We create two pointers start and end which are indexes where start = 0 and end = length of string minus 1
3. Create a StringBuilder object using input string
3. Run a while loop until start is less than end.
4. Check the letters are these indices.
5. If the letters are same, increment start and decrement end.
6. If they are different, replace lexicographically larger number with smaller one in the StringBuilder object.
7. Return the StringBuilder object after converting to String.


# Code
```
class Solution {
    public String makeSmallestPalindrome(String s) {
        int start = 0;
        int end = s.length()-1;

        StringBuilder newStr = new StringBuilder(s);
        while(start<end){
            char startChar = s.charAt(start);
            char endChar =  s.charAt(end);
            if(startChar != endChar){
                if(startChar<endChar)
                    newStr.setCharAt(end,startChar);
                else if(endChar<startChar)
                    newStr.setCharAt(start,endChar);
            }
            start++;
            end--;
        }
        return newStr.toString();
    }
}
```

