# Intuition
The goal is to modify the input string such that the resulting string is lexicographically smallest. To achieve this, we compare characters from both ends of the string and replace the larger character with the smaller one. This way, we ensure that we are making the string as small as possible while maintaining lexicographical order.

# Approach
1. Initialize two pointers 'i' at the beginning of the string and j at the end of the string.
2. Create a 'StringBuilder' to manipulate the string.
3. Iterate while 'i' is less than 'j'.
4. If the characters at positions i and j are different:
        -> Store the characters at positions 'i' and 'j' in variables 'c1' and 'c2'.
        -> Compare 'c1' and 'c2'. If 'c1' is lexicographically smaller, replace     character at position 'j' with 'c1', else replace character at position 'i' with 'c2'.
5. Move 'i' to the right and 'j' to the left.
6. Return the modified string using 'toString()' on the 'StringBuilder'.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)

- Space complexity: O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public String makeSmallestPalindrome(String s) {
        int i=0;
        int j=s.length()-1;
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(s);
        while(i<j){
            if(s.charAt(i)!=s.charAt(j)){
                int c1 = s.charAt(i);
                int c2 = s.charAt(j);
                if(c1<c2){
                    sb.setCharAt(j, s.charAt(i));
                }
                else{
                    sb.setCharAt(i, s.charAt(j));
                }
            }
            i++;
            j--;
        }
        return sb.toString();
    }
}
