# Approach
- Initialize n as the index of the last character in the string s.
- Initialize l as 0, representing the index of the first character in the string s.
- Convert the input string s into a character array charArray.
- Use a while loop to iterate over the characters from the beginning (l) and end (n) of the string towards the middle.
- For each pair of characters at indices l and n, check if they are not equal.
- If they are not equal, select the smaller of the two characters and assign it to both charArray[l] and charArray[n] to make them equal.
- Increment l and decrement n to move towards the middle of the string.
- Repeat steps 5 to 7 until l is less than or equal to n.

Finally, after all the iterations, the function returns the modified charArray as a new string representing the smallest palindrome.
# Complexity
- Time complexity : O(N)

- Space complexity : O(N)


![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/01548d59-e849-4ac9-8e56-72630d68005e_1690738879.945812.png)


# Code
```
class Solution {
    public String makeSmallestPalindrome(String s) {
    int n = s.length()-1;
    int l=0;
    char[] charArray = s.toCharArray();
    while(l<n)
    {
        if(charArray[l] != charArray[n]){
            char c = (char) Math.min(charArray[l],charArray[n]);
            charArray[l] = charArray[n]  = c;
        }
        l++;
        n--;
    }
    return new String(charArray);
    }
}
```

