# Intuition
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/fb9aed2c-96fd-474d-a975-7a76042c6467_1689953604.8667414.png)
The intuition behind this approach is to create the lexicographically smallest palindrome from a given string by using two pointers, one starting from the beginning of the string and the other from the end. We compare the characters at these two pointers and choose the smaller one to fill in the character array.

# Approach
We start by initializing two pointers, `l` and `r`, at the beginning and end of the string respectively. We also initialize a character array `chars` to store the characters of the palindrome.

```java
int n = s.length() - 1, l = 0, r = n - 1;
char[] chars = new char[n];
```

Next, we loop through the string to determine the characters to be filled into the array:

```java
while(l <= r) {
    char leftChar = s.charAt(l);
    char rightChar = s.charAt(r);
    char ch = ' ';
    if(leftChar < rightChar) {
        ch = leftChar;
    } else {
        ch = rightChar;
    }
    chars[l] = ch;
    chars[r] = ch;
    l++; r--;
}
```

We can simplify the `if-else` logic using the ternary operator:

```java
while(l <= r) {
    char leftChar = s.charAt(l);
    char rightChar = s.charAt(r);
    char ch = leftChar < rightChar ? leftChar : rightChar;
    chars[l] = ch;
    chars[r] = ch;
    l++; r--;
}
```

Furthermore, we can eliminate the variables `leftChar` and `rightChar` and directly assign the character to `chars` array

```java
while(l <= r) {
    chars[l++] = chars[r--] = (char) Math.min(s.charAt(l), s.charAt(r));
}
```

To make the code more concise, we can use a for loop and declare variables directly:

```java
for (int l = 0, r = n - 1; l <= r; l++, r--) {
    chars[l] = chars[r] = (char) Math.min(s.charAt(l), s.charAt(r));
}
```

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $O(n/2)$ ~ $O(n)$ (Since we loop through only half of the string)
- Space complexity: $O(n)$

# Code
```java
class Solution {
    public String makeSmallestPalindrome(String s) {
        int n = s.length(); 
        char[] chars = new char[n];
        for (int l = 0, r = n - 1; l <= r; l++, r--) {
