# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We can use some kind of data struct to hold the dictionary and apply a simple DP. While we could use a hash map to hold the dictionary, it's less efficient than a Trie because the way we search it.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We use a trie to hold the dictionary and search each index of the input string s to see where it can properly ends. The recursive relation is:
```
dp[i] = min {
  dp[j] if s[i: j) is a word 
}
```

**Note**: This problem can be viewed as an upgraded version of:
https://leetcode.com/problems/word-break/solutions/3860518/0ms-o-nw-mw-most-efficient-solution-simple-dp-with-trie/

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$\Theta(Nw + Mw)$$
where $N$ is the size of s, $M$ is the size of the dictionary and $w$ is the average size of the words in the dictionary.
The $Mw$ terms comes from the process of building the dictionary.
The $Nw$ terms comes from the dp process.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$\Theta(Mw)$$

# Code
```
class Trie {
 public:
  void Add(string_view word) {
    Node* node = &head_;
    for (char c : word) {
      node = NextOrInsert(node, c);
    }
    node->has_end = true;
  }

  struct Node {
    bool has_end = false;
    Node* children[26] = {};
  };

  class Walker {
   public:
    Walker(const Node* node) : node_(node) {}

    bool Advance(char c) {
      node_ = node_->children[c - 'a'];
      return node_ != nullptr;
    }

    bool IsWord() const {
      return node_->has_end;
    }

   private:
    const Node* node_;
  };

  Walker StartWalker() const {
    return Walker(&head_);
  }

 private:
  Node* NextOrInsert(Node* node, char c) {
    Node*& next = node->children[c - 'a'];
    if (next == nullptr) {
      next = &nodes_.emplace_back();
    }
    return next;
  }

  Node head_;
  std::deque<Node> nodes_;
};

class Solution {
public:
  int minExtraChar(string s, vector<string>& dictionary) {
    Trie trie;
    for (const string& word : dictionary) {
      trie.Add(word);
    }

    const int N = s.size();
    vector<int> dp(N + 1);  // extra chars needed for s[i:]
    for (int i = N - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
      Trie::Walker walker = trie.StartWalker();
      dp[i] = 1 + dp[i + 1];
      for (int j = i; j < N; ++j) {
        if (!walker.Advance(s[j])) {
          break;
        }
        if (walker.IsWord()) {
          dp[i] = min(dp[i], dp[j + 1]);
        }
      }
    }
    return dp[0];
  }
};
```

