# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This code utilizes dynamic programming to efficiently compute the minimum number of extra characters needed to form a given string using a set of substrings. By iteratively building substrings and using previously computed values, it determines the optimal solution.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

A vector dp of size n + 1 is created and initialized with the maximum possible integer value using numeric_limits<int>::max(). This vector will store the minimum number of extra characters required to form the substring ending at index i of the input string.

Two nested loops are used to iterate through all possible substrings of s. The outer loop iterates from index 1 to n, representing the end index of the substring, and the inner loop iterates from the current end index to index 1, representing the start index of the substring.

In each iteration of the nested loops, a substring is extracted from s using the substr function. This substring is checked against the substrings in the dict set using count. If a matching substring is found in the set, the minimum value of dp[i] is updated with the value of dp[j - 1], where j is the start index of the current substring.

After the inner loop finishes, the minimum value of dp[i] is compared with the value of dp[i - 1] + 1, which represents the case of adding an extra character at the end of the current substring. The smaller value is then stored in dp[i].

Finally, the function returns the value at index n of the dp vector, which represents the minimum number of extra characters required to form the entire input string s
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n2)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

