# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
It's a classic word matching problem, so `dynamic programming` is the first approach that came into my mind.

And one important clue is that, assuming $s_i = concat(s_j, word)$ where word is a string in the dictionary. The minimum extra characters in $s_i$ and $s_j$ are euqal.

Therefore, we can get a simple formula:
$dp[0] = 1$, when $s_0$ is not in the dictinoary 
$dp[0] = 0$, when $s_0$ is  in the dictinoary 
$dp[i] = min(dp[i-1]+1, dp[i-word.size()])$, otherwise

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

Because we want to check if a character matches the end of any word in the dictionary, we first insert the word in `dictionary` into a hash map, which is an `unordered_map<char, string>`in C++, by their ending characters.

Then iterate through the given string `s`. For index $i$, we check if there are some words matchs the end part of $s_i$. If it does, update the `dp[i]` based on whether it has less extra charaters in this case.

Last of all, returns the last element in the `dp` array, which represents the minimum number of extra characters of the given `s`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $O(n*m$), where n represents the length of `s` and m represents the total number of characters in dictionary
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $O(n+m)$. Because we need a hashmap to store all the strings in `dictionary` and an extra array `dp` to record the minimum number of extra characters in $s_i$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minExtraChar(string s, vector<string>& dictionary) {
        unordered_map<char, vector<string>> dict;
        for(const string& str: dictionary){
            dict[str.back()].push_back(str);
        } 

        vector<int> dp(s.length(), 0);
        dp[0] = 1; 
        for(int i=0; i<s.length(); ++i){
            if(i) dp[i] = dp[i-1] + 1;

            for(const string &word: dict[s[i]]){
                if(
                    (i >= (word.length()-1)) &&
                    (s.substr(i-word.length()+1, word.length()) == word)
                ){
                    if(i == (word.length() - 1)){
                         dp[i] = 0; 
                    }
                    else dp[i] = min(dp[i], dp[i - word.length()]);
                }
            }
        }

        return dp.back();
    }
};
```

